                                                                                                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="13017715" author="rmorrisey" created="Fri, 8 Apr 2011 22:35:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attached quickstart to show what on earth I&apos;m talking about. Note that the missing conditional comment is shown in wicket ajax debug.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025348" author="pedrosans" created="Tue, 26 Apr 2011 18:04:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Russell, I just tried to manually add a comment element in the page header element using JavaScript and IE is reporting a error in console: &quot;there are no support for this interface&quot;. You can change the ConditionalHeaderContributor to contribute a resource only if the browser matches. e.g using WebClientInfo&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025390" author="rmorrisey" created="Tue, 26 Apr 2011 19:16:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Pedro,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the suggestion! That&apos;s what I ended up doing. I would have liked to come up with a fix to contribute to wicket&apos;s javascript code; however, I could not determine a way to create a (working) IE conditional comment using javascript after the page load.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025756" author="akiraly" created="Wed, 27 Apr 2011 12:10:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This bug affects the 1.5 branch too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Adding a patch for trunk. It modifies wicket-ajax.js so comments from the ajax response are processed and attached to the html head too.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025838" author="mgrigorov" created="Wed, 27 Apr 2011 15:26:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attaching a quickstart for 1.5.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025840" author="mgrigorov" created="Wed, 27 Apr 2011 15:28:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The patch is applied to 1.5.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13025856" author="mgrigorov" created="Wed, 27 Apr 2011 15:51:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Now I&apos;m thinking that we can add IHeaderResponse.renderConditionalCssReference() which will create something like &amp;lt;comment&amp;gt; in the header-contribution.&lt;br/&gt;
Looks better to me.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
